# Licensing

This repository contains two kinds of material under two licences.

## Prose, illustrations, exercises, and the book in general

Licensed under the **Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License**
(CC BY 4.0). You are free to share and adapt the material, including for
commercial purposes, provided you give appropriate credit, provide a link to
the licence, and indicate whether changes were made.

The full legal text is in [`LICENSE-CC-BY-4.0`](LICENSE-CC-BY-4.0).
Summary: <https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/>.

This applies to:

- everything in `book/`, `concepts/`, and `code/sim/SPEC.md` (the prose),
- the diagrams under `artwork/` and any in-line figures,
- the exercise specifications.

## Code samples and reference solutions

Licensed under **MIT** ([`LICENSE-MIT`](LICENSE-MIT)) **or Apache-2.0**
([`LICENSE-APACHE-2.0`](LICENSE-APACHE-2.0)) at your option — the standard
Rust dual-licence pattern.

This applies to:

- reference Rust solutions in `book/trunk/*_solutions.md`,
- the through-line simulator code under `code/sim/` (when written),
- helper scripts in `tools/`,
- `build.py`.

## Why split

CC BY for the prose lets readers redistribute and adapt the book — translate it,
excerpt it for courses, mirror it on Codeberg or elsewhere — provided they
attribute. MIT/Apache-2.0 for the code lets the code be incorporated into other
projects under the same terms most of the Rust ecosystem uses.

If you want to use a fragment and the line between prose and code is unclear,
either licence applies — pick whichever is more useful to you.
